Bacon’s solution of the difficulty by referring the explosion to the ‘conflict of two bodies,’ and his lauguage about the ‘crude spirit which is in nitre,’ are thoroughly characteristic both of his own chemical views and, generally, of those of his time. Chemistry‚ we must recollect, had hardly as yet put on a scientilic form, and, moreover, it was peculiarly encumbered by the use of a fanciful and metaphorical language.

As to the true explanation of the great explosive power of gunpowder, it ‘is due to the sudden development of a large volume of gaseous bodies, chieflyconsisting of nitrogen and carbonic enhydride, which, at the ordinary temperature of the air, would occupy a space equal to about 300 times the bulk os the powder used; but from the intense heat developed at the moment of the explosion, the dilatlon amounts to at least 1500 times the volume of the gunpowder employed!
